metadata.name: Ecos de Calma #74
metadata.description:
Through algorithms and javascript code, each artwork comes to life with unique patterns and forms, evoking a sense of inner peace. The careful selection of the color palette recreates the magic of the transition between the softness of morning or evening light, with warm and subtle tones that intertwine in harmony.

'Ecos de Calma' invites viewers to explore their own sense of serenity and find moments of calmness in contemplating these generative creations. Let yourself be enveloped by the experience and immerse yourself in the subtle nuances and harmony of each color palette, where the moon and the tree come together to create a scene of tranquility and beauty.

Features:
15 Color Palettes.
5 Canvas Sizes.
Moon: Full Moon / Waning Crescent.
One or two hills.

Press "S" to download the image.

Created by Fernando Cabral.

metadata.name: Breeding Grounds #1
metadata.description:
Social Networks.
Molecular Clouds.
Neuronal Circuitries.
Quantum Mechanical Structures.

Blurring Boundaries.
Infinite Self-Similarities.

Total.
Mess.

Perfect.
Order.

/////
Each element (besides the painting ground textures) is based on the underlying subdivided grid which is sometimes exposed like some kind of preliminary drawing.

Note on the split:
After seeing some of the outputs, Sermin had a dream about “Breeding Grounds” and I decided to incorporate events and feelings from her dream into the project. That's how the names of the color palettes came about. Thank you for naming them, Sermin!

Press 's' to save a .png with the current resolution (2000x3000).
If you want a file with higher resolution and/or without the “Painting Ground Textures” for printing please contact me via Twitter or Discord. 

/////
Created with p5.js

Twitter: @serminmin / @pxlshrd

metadata.name: Glossolalia #283
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse… which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it’s about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It’s less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append “&density=2” to the url to double the size, “&density=3” to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append “&grain=##” to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #80
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Action; System #8
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of François Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl
License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Identity Diversity #18
metadata.description:
Are most collectors of art on fxhash heterosexual, neurotypical, mentally healthy cis men? 
We don't know. 

The default token for this artwork is ours. This shows our identification as a neptunic, genderfluid person with a dissociative disorder, autism, adhd, dyslexia, sensory processing difficulties and an eating disorder who has considered suicide. 

Really - we are extraordinarily happy most of the time!

Our hope is that people mint this token with self representative parameters so that the gallery will hint at our diversity - or uniformity - as a community. 

All of the aspects of this artwork are linked to elements of identity except for the background pattern, which is simply personal preference. 

Use keys 2, 3 & 4 to render at higher resolutions.

metadata.name: Flowers and Sky #228
metadata.description:
Flowers and Sky

Using natural brushstrokes and bright colors, this generative system creates stunning scenes of flower-filled meadows under a brilliant sky. It is inspired by the masters of impressionist art and aims to capture the beauty of nature.

Every leaf, petal, cloud, and sunray are generated from code using simulated brushstrokes. The flowers and trees are suggestive only and do not depict real species.

There are 8 formal features that have many values in order to generate a wide variety of outputs. The only rare feature is a SkyMode of 'Eclipse' which occurs in 3% of the outputs.

--------------------------

This is a 100% code generated project. Outputs are created at a default resolution of 1500 x 1000.

Click on the output and use these keys to change the resolution or save the output:
's' - save at current resolution

'2' - change to  3000 x 2000 resolution
'3' - change to  4500 x 3000 resolution
...
'8' - change to 12000 x 8000 resolution

URL Parameters: You can also set the resolution in the url.
To change the resolution append &res=2 (or 3-8)

Copyright 2023 Jeff Clark

metadata.name: Dencity #80
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ❤️, code and p5js.
